diff:1670195761:1667787987:=70,88d69%0a%3c #foxbegin 221204-231601-447090#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Technologies Overlooking Needs of Deaf Community %0a%3c -> - johnternullo%0a%3c -> [-04.12.2022 - 15:16-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221204-231601-447090 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Although there have been attempts to develop machine translation technologies for signed languages, many of them do not recognize important needs of the Deaf community. For example, the SignAloud gloves developed by the University of Washington show that people developing these technologies frequently fail to recognize the importance of aspects of sign languages like facial and body movements apart from hand movements.%0a%3c %0a%3c Another common complaint about technologies like this is that they are often made only to serve hearing people by making signed languages intelligible to them while removing nuances present in signed languages due to how they differ so much from spoken languages. In addition, Deaf people are the ones who are expected to carry around these gloves and the technology required for machine translation, adding on to the burdens they already have.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/11/why-sign-language-gloves-dont-help-deaf-people/545441/%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221204-231601-447090#%0a
